column48:
The design and construction for temporary education facilities for Hope Community School, Southampton, on behalf of the Education Funding Agency (EFA), at the site of Central Hall, Southampton for completion by August 2017.  

Works are required to an existing community and events building to provide temporary accommodation for a new Free School (Hope Community School) in Southampton.  

The proposed works include the remodelling of existing storage and office spaces to provide temporary accommodation for a total of 120 pupils within an existing community and events centre. These works include:

-	Reconfiguration including minor structural alterations and light refurbishment of internal layouts.
-	Installation/reconfiguration for new toilet block  
-	Associated works to modify the mechanical and electrical systems, (lighting, fire alarm, heating, access control) to be inline with the new reconfigured floor plate layouts
-	External works to create secure outside pupil play space and introduction of new access to the building.

The principal contractor will be appointed on a D&B basis and responsible for progressing all survey and design development based on specifications and indicative outline design.  The proposed form of contract is the JCT 2011 Intermediate Building Contract with Contractor's Design (ICD), with EFA standard amendments.

The final appointment of the contractor will be on the basis of the criteria to be published in the tender documents.

The tender documents will be available on 4th April 2017, with tender returns due by 12 noon on 28 April 2017.

column47: NHS Leeds: Direct Access Endoscopy and Gastroenterology Services
column48:
NHS Leeds West CCG, NHS Leeds North CCG and NHS Leeds South and East CCG wish to contract with providers on an AQP (Any Qualified Provider) basis to provide Direct Access Endoscopy (Gastroscopy and Flexible Sigmoidoscopy) Services (Lot 1) and Gastroenterology and Colonoscopy Services (Lot2) for patients registered with a Leeds GP practice.
The services are offered in two lots and providers may apply for either Lot 1, or Lots 1 & 2.    
The Commissioners require the above services from providers with staff qualified to appropriate levels of skill and experience, the ability to integrate with the E-Referral System, the ability to integrate secondary care image exchange systems, robust performance management systems and stringent levels of clinical governance.  The provider must have access to suitably equipped and quality assured premises and be able to mobilise within three months.
It is expected that the successful applicant will either be able to or be working towards submission of activity data via Secondary Uses Service (SUS) and to be able to or working towards integration with primary care information systems.
The service specification and the electronic application form can be found online at www.nhssourcing.co.uk .
Applications will be accepted from current providers and new applicants wishing to provide the services for Leeds patients. 
The successful providers will be required to sign the NHS Standard Contract for the service, accepting all terms and conditions. 
The services will be commissioned using the Any Qualified Provider process under which assurance of competence, quality and safety standards is required. Providers will be eligible to join the qualified provider list subject to demonstrating competency against specified criteria.
Activity will be paid at National Tariff rates and it is expected that this will include the price of any pre-procedure preparations. 
A CQUIN scheme will be available.
It should be noted that under the AQP model, there will be no guarantees of volume payments in the contract award.
The commissioners will require mobilisation of services within three months after contract award

Additional information: 
The contract duration is for 3(+1+1) years. For further information about this service, to access the service specification for this service and to apply to provide this service, please visit www.nhssourcing.co.uk.  The project number for this opportunity is pqq_29354.

The Deadline for submissions is 12:00 (mid-day) Tuesday 18 April 2017.

If applicants are asked clarification questions during the evaluation stage they will have 48 hours to respond.

column47: Raingarden Demonstration Project in Somerset
column48: Following the severe and prolonged flooding in Somerset in 2012 and 2013/14 the local authorities were tasked with preparing a 20 year Flood Action Plan. This plan also led to the formation of the Somerset Rivers Authority (SRA). The SRA is run by a Board of local authority partners from the five District Councils, Somerset County Council, the Environment Agency, the Parrett and Axe Brue Internal Drainage Boards, the Wessex Regional Flood & Coastal Committee and Natural England. Through the SRA, SCC, along with these other partners, is working to deliver the actions contained in the Flood Action Plan. Feedback following the flooding identified the negative impact of development on flood risk and a perception that Sustainable Drainage Systems (SuDS) to help address urban run-off are not as widespread as they should be. Accordingly, one of the actions in the flood action plan is to implement a rain garden demonstration project.

column48:
Hampshire County Council invites applications from suitably experienced organisations who wish to be considered for selection to tender for the supply of Intensive Family Support Services as part of the 'Troubled Families' programme engages and supports Hampshire families. The service provides skilled and experienced workers to assess need, develop and co-ordinate plans and provide interventions including evidence based programmes to achieve the key aims of the of the National Troubled Families Programme. 
      
      The contract will commence on 1st April 2017 and will be for a period of Three years.
      
      Interested parties should register their interest in the project via the In-Tend website https://in-tendhost.co.uk/hampshire, and complete and submit the tender return document together with any supporting information requested by 14.00hrs on Friday 18th November 2016.  
      
      How to obtain the Tender Documents
      The Tender documents can be accessed when logged into In-Tend by selecting 'View Details' on the relevant tender advert and clicking the 'Express Interest' tab. Once in the tender there are five tabs - 'Tender', ('ITT - documents', 'Correspondence', 'Clarifications' and 'History'. Select the 2nd tab (ITT - documents) where you will find useful information under 'Tender Details' continue to scroll down to the heading 'Tender Documents Received' where you will be able to view / download the documents.
      
      Opting In and Out
      Please note you are required to 'Opt In' before you can access the 'My tender Return' to start populating your response. 
      
      The 'Opt Out' functionality will also be available throughout the duration of the tender process. Opting out will give you the option of declaring you no longer want to receive any further communication in relation to this tender along with the opportunity of providing comments and feedback for this decision.
      You can choose to 'Opt In' at any time during the tender process if you initially decided to 'Opt Out'.

      Further Guidance

      Receiving Notification Emails

column46: FWRECR16132BEIS - Research into Knowledge Exchange and Commercialisation Issues
column47: FWRECR16132BEIS - Research into Knowledge Exchange and Commercialisation Issues
column48:
BEIS wish to commission research to further explore the issues in interactions between universities and business. The evidence to date concerning specific barriers to collaboration in the relationships has been primarily anecdotal and BEIS wish to build a more robust evidence base to better inform policy.
The research has 3 main aims:
The first aim is to validate, and refine as appropriate, a proposed model of KEC, including Influencing Factors, Transaction Types and Transaction Stages.
Secondly, the research should then apply this model to increase understanding of how different factors influence the development of knowledge exchange policies and practices, and how certain factors create complexity or barriers leading to problems in practice.
Thirdly, the research should explore how and where improvements might be made to KEC practice (in both universities and business), governance or leadership, including the role of improved information in improving understanding and overcoming barriers to collaboration.

column47: Provision of Community Myalgic Encephalomyelitis (ME) and Chronic Fatigue Syndrome (CFS) Service
column48:
NHS Ipswich and East Suffolk Clinical Commissioning Group are publishing this notice on behalf of the seven CCGs which cover the counties of Suffolk and Norfolk.  

The CCGs currently commission a community based GP with Special Interest (GPwSI) and Occupational Therapy based service that sees patients with mild to moderate ME and CFS. The CCGs are interested in transforming this into a consultant led model consistent with the current international consensus evidence base for ME and CFS.

The CCGs are seeking to understand if there are providers who could and would be interested in delivering these services in a range of locations across Norfolk and Suffolk.

The aim of the service will be to improve outcomes (particularly for those with severe ME), increase ongoing support and provide a more holistic multi-disciplinary team approach to care. The total annual budget for the community element is anticipated to be in the region of 500,000 GBP. 

The service will be required to triage referrals, diagnose for ME or CFS, and agree management plans with patients which may be long term specialist follow up, OT led management or short or group intervention. 

In addition, the service would be expected to provide advice to referrers and offer training to increase awareness of ME and CFS and to up-skill referrers. 

The purpose of this notice is to invite providers to contact Ipswich & East Suffolk CCG if they are potentially interested in delivering the required services. This PIN is not commencing a procurement process; any future procurement activity in relation to the services that are the subject of this PIN may be the subject of a separate notice. The Ipswich and East Suffolk CCG is not liable for any costs incurred by those expressing an interest in this process. To express an interest and receive a copy of the outline service specification please email the named contact in this advert by 12:00 24/04/2017.

column47: Management and Operation of the Recycling Village at Middlefields, South Shields
column48:
The Recycling Village is provided to discharge the Authority's statutory duty under Section 51 of the Environmental Protection Act 1990.
The facility comprises five aspects:
1. A covered tipping area with a wide range of containers in which to deposit materials brought onto the Recycling Village, with the emphasis on material segregation and storage.
2. The transport of collected materials to various destinations to enable its processing or disposal.
3. A "Bring Site" for recyclable materials.
4. Reception and storage areas for Waste Electrical and Electronic Equipment (WEEE) and Post-Consumer Batteries.
5. The Windmill Warehouse, operated by the Authority's partner, Groundwork, acts as a catalyst for environmental, recycled and reclaimed products and information about the environment.
The Authority requires a Service that will primarily assist with the first and second aspects set out above, but which will also contribute to the successful and efficient operation of the others.

column47: AHS5187 - Specialist Tobacco Cessation Service
column48:
The Council requires the services of an organisation or group of organisations to reduce the local prevalence of smoking and tobacco use.

The primary focus of the new service will be to target the tobacco cessation activity for all local smokers with specialist support for the following who may have additional of complex needs;

	Black and minority ethnic groups (BME) 
	Pregnant women
	Those living with mental health (MH) or severe (SMI) issues
	Those living with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)
	Young people (17 and under) 
	Lesbian, gay, bisexual and trans people
	Residents with substance misuse issues including alcohol and illicit substances

Requirements of the service are:
	To provide an easy to access specialist stop smoking service for all smokers. 
	To provide intensive support for smokers from targeted segments of the population (as specified in the statement of requirements in section 4).
	To provide a treatment and support programme adhering to evidence based best practice.
	To successfully support people in quitting smoking and tobacco use, with particular focus on high need cohorts of the local population. 
	To achieve high level of user satisfaction.
	To provide system leadership and a source of expertise for the local smoking cessation services in Tower Hamlets.

column47: 11+ Services - Information Advice and Guidance
column48:
The Service will 

 Promote and develop Young Peoples independence by enabling them to make informed choice over issues which affect them. This will increase their knowledge and understanding of their rights and promote self-help where it is appropriate in order to improve resilience and enable resources to be directed at those most in need.
 
 Provide a specific youth advice Service, which is attractive to and easily accessible by Young People aged 11 to 19
 
 Provide information and advice through a variety of means and settings including but not limited to:
  Face to face 
 Online 
 Telephone 
 Across education and community settings which Young People can access 

 Provide Young People, especially those who are vulnerable with free, impartial, independent and confidential information, advice, support and casework services, to meet their needs on a diverse range of issues that are frequently inter-related which may include, but is not limited to;
  Social Welfare: Social welfare issues including but not limited to benefits, housing, debt, employment, legal rights
  Emotional resilience: Mental and emotional health issues, including but not limited to anxiety, stress, depression, low self-esteem, self-harm and bullying
  Personal and health issues: Wider personal and health issues, including but not limited to relationship and family difficulties, sexual health, drugs and alcohol, healthy eating, smoking
  Practical skills: Practical issues, including but not limited to careers, money management, independent living skills

column47: Mental Health - Bereavement and suicide prevention service for residents of Barnet
column48:
Nationally, almost one in four British adults and one in ten children experience a diagnosable common mental health problem at any given time in  their lives. In Barnet this approximates to 40,000 people.

Reducing the prevalence of common mental health disorders such as anxiety and depressive disorders is a major public health concern. In 2007 the annual cost to treat depression and anxiety disorders in England was nearly 3billion with an addition impact of around 13billion in lost earnings among people of working age.  

The Five Year Forward View for mental health states that
'Three quarters of people with mental health problems receive no support at all. Among those who are helped, too few have access to the full range of interventions recommended by National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE), including properly prescribed medication and psychological therapy.

column47: Resilience Programme to Build Emotional Health and Well-being for Children & Young People attending Nottinghamshire Schools
column48: Nottinghamshire County Council is seeking to commission an evidence based resilience programme to build emotional health and well-being for children and young people attending south Nottinghamshire schools, partly funded by Broxtowe, Gedling and Rushcliffe Clinical Commissioning Groups. The provider will develop and deliver an evidence-based resilience programme in schools that will improve the emotional health and wellbeing and resilience of children and young people. It is anticipated that there will be three stages: 1.	Planning: identifying & engaging schools, and ensuring their commitment to sustainable whole school change, and planning activity based on the schools individual needs 2.	Activity: delivering the evidence based programme as a whole school approach,( this means school leaders, staff, children and young people which may include approaches such as training the trainer and pupils and students as coaches, mentors or teachers.) and ensuring that schools have the understanding, the knowledge, skills and resources to continue independent delivery of the programme via a whole schools approach 3.	Sustainability: collecting data and measuring impact of the programme, and providing trouble-shooting support to schools The Council is seeking bids that offer value for money through efficiency and innovative thinking and Bidders will be required to identify the level of service that will be provided for the funds available.

column47: CCCC17A16 - National Infrastructure Assessment: National Estimates for Capture of Land Value Uplift
column48:
The National Infrastructure Commission ("NIC") is an executive agency of the Treasury that enables long term strategic decision making to build effective and efficient infrastructure for the UK.

The purpose of this requirement is to appoint an external provider who will deliver the following:

1               A tool/calculator that provides estimates in land value uplift following from changes in land purpose or infrastructure improvements. This tool should:

a. be as detailed and comprehensive as possible by, for example, providing estimates for differentials in land value changes across locations at the lowest geographical level possible as well as for all different types of mechanisms or broader reforms in place;

b.  be flexible to allow to appraise the impact of alternative mechanisms or to easily incorporate relevant policy changes; and

c. comprise a sensitivity analysis to allow for potential deviations in the estimates of land value uplifts that can arise due to the uncertainty they are subject to.

2               A rich and extensive database that gathers information on the value and designation (change in land use) of land and how this has changed over time, ideally at the lowest possible geographical level. The data and the model should be provided either in Excel (preferably) or Stata formats only.

3               Extensive model documentation to allow the NIC to use the model independently of the Provider. This documentation should include clear and simple guidance that will allow the NIC as end-user to operate the model, as well as a clear explanation of the model structure and logic, its methodology, underlying assumptions and limitations; inputs required and outputs expected.

For full details of the requirement please refer to Appendix B Statement of Requirement.

Additional information: How to apply Instructions to Potential Providers:

Potential Providers must first be registered on the Crown Commercial Service e-Sourcing Suite in order to respond to the Procurement. If you have not yet registered on the e-Sourcing Suite, this can be done online athttps://gpsesourcing.cabinetoffice.gov.ukby following the link 'Register for CCS e-Sourcing'.

Please note that, to register, you must have a valid DUNS number (as provided byDun and Bradstreet) for the organisation which you are registering, who will be entering into a contract if invited to do so at the Invitation to Tender stage. Potential Providers should note that it could take up to 10 working days to obtain a DUNS number.
Full instructions for registration and use of the system can be found at:
http://gps.cabinetoffice.gov.uk/i-am-supplier/respond-tender

Once you have registered on the e-Sourcing Suite, you will need to express your interest by emailingExpressionOfInterest@Crowncommercial.gov.uk[The dead line for expressing an interest in the Request for Information event is[insert time, day and date (DD/MM/YYYY)]][Delete if not applicable (ie Open competitions)]

Your email must clearly state:

Crown Commercial Service will then process your registration and assign your organisation to the opportunity. The registered user will receive a notification email to alert them once this has been done.

It is advised however that Potential Providers register as soon as practically possible in order to receive the Invitation to Tender and have a sufficient amount of time to respond. Crown Commercial Service is not able to offer any extensions to the advertised procurement timetable.
